nodes.bodyText:
As a general observation, always think twice about what tree is reported, it will define what is highlighted in the different products, if the tree is too big, it will result in something ugly.
This is especially true for method invocation: arguments can be unusually long, a huge lambda for example!
In this case, it will always be true or false, it can't go wrong... Can it?
First, it can be more than just literals, if you look at line 78, .asConstant(Boolean.class); also checks if the tree is a reference to a constant. So this code:
private static final boolean ignoreTest = false;
// ...
assumeTrue(ignoreTest);
will also report an issue.
Then, what if someone is using strange formatting, fully qualified name...
Putting all together, you can end up with something like that:
org.junit.Assume.assumeTrue(
// We use assumeTrue to ignore test because ...
MyLongTestHelperClass.IGNORE_TEST_WITH_ASSUME_TRUE
);
with everything highlighted!
I agree that this is really unlikely to happen, but it illustrates well what can go wrong!
I believe reporting on the method name is enough here.
By the way, you can use ExpressionUtils::methodName for this purpose.

